{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"mimetype":"text/x-r-source","name":"R","pygments_lexer":"r","version":"3.6.0","file_extension":".r","codemirror_mode":"r"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/rasheedatjimoh/bellabeat-wellness-company-capstone-project?scriptVersionId=103634541\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown","outputs":[],"execution_count":0},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# This R environment comes with many helpful analytics packages installed\n# It is defined by the kaggle/rstats Docker image: https://github.com/kaggle/docker-rstats\n# For example, here's a helpful package to load\n\nlibrary(tidyverse) # metapackage of all tidyverse packages\n\n# Input data files are available in the read-only \"../input/\" directory\n# For example, running this (by clicking run or pressing Shift+Enter) will list all files under the input directory\n\nlist.files(path = \"../input\")\n\n# You can write up to 20GB to the current directory (/kaggle/working/) that gets preserved as output when you create a version using \"Save & Run All\" \n# You can also write temporary files to /kaggle/temp/, but they won't be saved outside of the current session","metadata":{"_uuid":"051d70d956493feee0c6d64651c6a088724dca2a","_execution_state":"idle"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Summary of case study**\n\n—Bellabeat a high tech company founded by Urška Sršen and Sando Mur in 2013 has a range of smart health-focused products for women. This case study analyses external health and fitness data to provide recommendations for Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.\n\n**Phase 1: ASK**\n\nIdentify the business task :Use insights from analysis of non-Bellabeat smart device usage to provide marketing strategy recommendations for Bellabeat. \n\nStakeholders: Urška Sršen and Sando Mur, Bellabeat marketing analytics team.\n\n\n**Phase 2: PREPARE**\n\nData was downloaded from [dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit)\n\nData was from a public domain and made available through [Mobius](https://www.kaggle.com/arashnic)\n\nI unzipped the folder and found that the dataset contains 18 csv files. These files contained data recorded by the fitbit smart device.\n\n**Limitations of data**\n\n1. The gender of the participants in this study was not specified. Bellabeat focuses on wellness products for women.\n2. This dataset wasn’t current. It was last updated 2 years ago. 3. The sample size contained in this dataset was small , and raises the question of sampling bias.\n4. This is an external data which means its less reliable for our analysis.\n\n\n**Install and load packages**\n\nFirst I installed and loaded the packages below","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"install.packages(\"tidyverse\")\nlibrary(tidyverse)\ninstall.packages(\"here\")\nlibrary(here)\ninstall.packages(\"skimr\")\nlibrary(skimr)\ninstall.packages(\"janitor\")\nlibrary(janitor)\ninstall.packages(\"ggpubr\")\nlibrary(ggpubr)\ninstall.packages(\"lubridate\")\nlibrary(lubridate)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i created a folder for the project and uploaded the data to this folder. I set my working directory to this folder so i can import the files from there. The dataset i uploaded to this folder were on daily calories, daily sleep, daily steps, daily intensities and daily activity..\n\nThen I imported my data using the read_csv() function.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_calories <- read_csv(\"dailyCalories_merged.csv\")\ndaily_steps <- read_csv(\"dailySteps_merged.csv\")\ndaily_intensities <- read_csv(\"dailyIntensities_merged.csv\")\ndaily_activity <- read_csv(\"dailyActivity_merged.csv\")\ndaily_sleep <- read_csv(\"sleepDay_merged.csv\")","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I previewed the datasets with the head() and glimpse() functions","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"head(daily_calories)\nhead(daily_steps)\nhead(daily_intensities)\nhead(daily_activity)\nhead(daily_sleep)\nglimpse(daily_activity)\nglimpse(daily_calories)\nglimpse(daily_intensities)\nglimpse(daily_steps)\nglimpse(daily_sleep)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This helped to confirm the dataset i uploaded were the correct ones\n\n**Phase 3: PROCESS**\n\nI used the following steps in the data cleaning process:\n\n— 1. format all column names to lower case for consistency using the clean_names() function","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"clean_names(daily_activity)\ndaily_activity<- rename_with(daily_activity, tolower)\nclean_names(daily_calories)\ndaily_calories <- rename_with(daily_calories, tolower)\nclean_names(daily_intensities)\ndaily_intensities <- rename_with(daily_intensities, tolower)\nclean_names(daily_steps)\ndaily_steps <- rename_with(daily_steps, tolower)\nclean_names(daily_sleep)\ndaily_sleep <- rename_with(daily_sleep, tolower)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— 2. The date/datetime column is represented in the 5 datasets as follows:\n\ndaily_activity = activitydate daily_calories = activityday daily_intesities = activityday daily_steps = activityday daily_sleep = sleepday\n\nFor consistency, I renamed all of these columns in each dataset to “date’ using the rename() function","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% rename (date = activitydate)\ndaily_calories <- daily_calories %>% rename (date = activityday)\ndaily_intensities <- daily_intensities %>% rename (date = activityday)\ndaily_steps <- daily_steps %>% rename (date = activityday)\ndaily_sleep <- daily_sleep %>% rename(date = sleepday)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— 3. I checked that the column names are now in lower case, and “date” is used to refer to date/datetime in all 5 datasets. using the colnames() function:","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"colnames(daily_activity)\ncolnames(daily_calories)\ncolnames(daily_intensities)\ncolnames(daily_steps)\ncolnames(daily_sleep)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— 4. I inspected the structure of our dataset using str() function","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"str(daily_activity)\nstr(daily_calories)\nstr(daily_intensities)\nstr(daily_steps)\nstr(daily_sleep)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This showed that the date column were in chr format.\n\n— 5. formatted this column to date and in the daily sleep dataset i extracted the date from datetime.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_activity <- daily_activity %>%\n  mutate(date = as_date(date, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))\ndaily_calories <- daily_calories %>%\n  mutate(date = as_date(date, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))\ndaily_intensities <- daily_intensities %>%\n  mutate(date = as_date(date, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))\ndaily_steps <- daily_steps %>%\n  mutate(date = as_date(date, format = \"%m/%d/%Y\"))\ndaily_sleep <- daily_sleep %>%\n  mutate(date = as_date(date,format =\"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\" , tz=Sys.timezone()))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— 6. I checked that our dates are now in date format and are consistent using the glimpse() function","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"glimpse(daily_activity)\nglimpse(daily_calories)\nglimpse(daily_intensities)\nglimpse(daily_steps)\nglimpse(daily_sleep)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I confirmed consistency of the date columns\n\n— 7. I checked the number of unique users in each dataset,and removed duplicates in the datasets.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"n_unique(daily_activity$id)\nn_unique(daily_calories$id)\nn_unique(daily_intensities$id)\nn_unique(daily_steps$id)\nn_unique(daily_sleep$id)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"–This shows 33 users for each dataset apart from the daily_sleep dataset that sampled 24 users","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sum(duplicated(daily_activity))\nsum(duplicated(daily_calories))\nsum(duplicated(daily_intensities))\nsum(duplicated(daily_steps))\nsum(duplicated(daily_sleep))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"—this shows a duplicate of 3 in the daily_sleep dataset only\n\n— Then i removed duplicates from the daily_sleep dataset","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_sleep <- daily_sleep %>%\n  distinct() %>%\n  drop_na()","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— and verified that duplicates have been removed","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sum(duplicated(daily_sleep))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"sum(duplicated(daily_sleep))","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"n_unique(daily_sleep$id)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"the sample size was still 24.Now that the data is clean, I moved to the analysis phase.\n\n**merging of datasets**\n\n—Before the analysis and visualization phases i merged some of the datasets i was interested in getting insights from.\n\nFirst, i merged the daily calories and daily_steps.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_calories_steps <- merge(daily_calories,daily_steps, by=c (\"id\", \"date\"))\nglimpse(daily_calories_steps)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"then i merged the daily_activity and daily_sleep dataset.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_data <- merge (daily_activity, daily_sleep, by = c(\"id\", \"date\"))\nglimpse(daily_data)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"— I then used n_unique() function to confirm this dataset has just 24 participants.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Phase 4 & 5: ANALYZE and SHARE**\n\n— first let see what insights we can get from our calories and steps dataset","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(daily_calories_steps)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"—Here we can see that the mean number of steps walked by the 24 participants in this merged dataset is 7,638. This is significantly less than the recommended 10,000 steps that should be taken daily.\n\nBellabeat can use this information to install reminders in its app to remind its users to take walks when they haven’t clocked their daily 10k steps. This is similar to way the apple watch reminds its users to stand for 1 minute every hour.\n\nNext i wanted to see the relationship between steps walked and calories burned daily\n\n— first i installed ggplot2","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"install.packages(\"ggplot2\")\nlibrary(ggplot2)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i created a scatterplot","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(daily_calories_steps, aes(x=calories, y=steptotal))+\n  geom_jitter() +\n  geom_smooth(color = \"red\") + \n  labs(title = \"Daily Steps vs Calories\", x = \"Calories Burned\", y= \"Daily Steps\") ","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:9692e648-8922-45b3-8af0-65f8e9ca759b.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"9692e648-8922-45b3-8af0-65f8e9ca759b.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As expected, participants burned more calories as they walked more.\n\nNext i wanted to see what days of the week users take more steps(walk) and what days they walk less.\n\nI used the daily_calories_steps merged dataset for this using the following steps: 1. I grouped the dataset by days","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"days_calories_steps <- daily_calories_steps %>%\n  mutate(days = weekdays(date))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then ordered the new dataset by days of the week","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"days_calories_steps$days <-ordered(days_calories_steps$days, levels=c(\"Monday\", \"Tuesday\", \"Wednesday\", \"Thursday\",\n\"Friday\", \"Saturday\", \"Sunday\"))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then looked for the daily calories and number of steps walked daily","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"days_calories_steps <-days_calories_steps%>%\n  group_by(days) %>%\n  summarize (daily_steps = mean(steptotal), daily_calories = mean(calories))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I previewed this new dataset","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"head(days_calories_steps)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i plotted a bar graph to visualize the daily steps walked relative to the average daily steps.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":" ggplot(days_calories_steps) +\n      geom_col(aes(days, daily_steps), fill = \"blue\") +\n      geom_hline(yintercept = 7638) +\n      labs(title = \"Steps Walked per Day\", x= \"days of the week\", y = \"number of steps\") +\n      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45,vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:08402320-9aa2-4e6b-86e2-963c05b970d7.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"08402320-9aa2-4e6b-86e2-963c05b970d7.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"—this shows that the users walked least on sundays. Perharps, because it was the end of the week and a rest day, users were less keen on being active. Bellabeat can use this information to send reminders via the app to its users to walk more on sundays.\n\n#####Then i moved to the merged daily_data table (Remember the daily data table is from combining daily_activity and daily_sleep).\n\nFirst, I wanted to see if there was a correlation between number of calories burned daily and amount of sleep.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(daily_data, aes(x=totalminutesasleep, y=calories))+\n  geom_jitter() +\n  geom_smooth(color = \"red\") + \n  labs(title = \"Daily Sleep vs Calories\", x = \"Calories Burned\", y= \"Total Sleep(in minutes)\") ","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:cb511557-9d55-4527-89bb-2461f2887497.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"cb511557-9d55-4527-89bb-2461f2887497.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"from the plot, we can see no correlation between calories burned and amount of sleep gotten\n\nNext, I summarized the daily_data table to see what insights we can get from about sleep and activity level of the users.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"summary(daily_data)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"From this, we can see that the mean amount of sleep in minutes was 419.2 which translates to about 6.98 hours daily.This is in line with the recommendation of getting at least 7 hours of sleep every night. According to [CareATC](https://www.careatc.com/improving-health/7-reasons-to-sleep-at-least-7-hours-each-night#:~:text=%207%20Reasons%20to%20Sleep%20at%20Least%207,role%20in%20the%20production%20of%20hunger...%20More%20), getting at least 7 hours of sleep per night lowers the risk of obesity, can build immunity and helps to balance blood sugars.\n\nNext I wanted to see if there was a positive correlation in total time in bed and total minutes asleep","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(daily_data, aes(x=totaltimeinbed, y=totalminutesasleep))+\n  geom_jitter() +\n  geom_smooth(color = \"red\") + \n  labs(title = \"Time in Bed vs Amount of Sleep\", x = \"Time in bed (in minutes)\", y= \"Amount of sleep(in minutes)\") ","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:5ee100fc-dfce-4144-b949-42ad16b967a3.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"5ee100fc-dfce-4144-b949-42ad16b967a3.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The almost positive correlation shows that user got more sleep when they spent more time in bed. Bellabeat can use this insight to send reminder notifications to users so they know what time to go to bed so they can get their daily recommended 7hrs of sleep.\n\nI also wanted to see what the activity levels of users look like. For this i used the following steps:\n\nFirst, i created new dataframes each for sum of each activity level from the daily_data dataframe","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sedentary<-sum(daily_data$sedentaryminutes)\nvery_active<-sum(daily_data$veryactiveminutes)\nfairly_active<-sum(daily_data$fairlyactiveminutes)\nlightly_active<-sum(daily_data$lightlyactiveminutes)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I created a new table that consists of the sum of all of these minutes","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"activity_level<- c(Sedentary=sedentary,VeryActive=very_active,FairlyActive=fairly_active,LightlyActive=lightly_active)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i plotted a bar to visualize my results","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"barplot(activity_level, main=\"Activity Level in Minutes\", col=c(\"red\", \"green\", \"blue\", \"yellow\"))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:f755c358-45cf-4ffb-88f4-4ec0265901da.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"f755c358-45cf-4ffb-88f4-4ec0265901da.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This shows that majority of the users were living a sedentary lifestyle. Bellabeat could use this information to send reminders to its users to take more walks, do more excercise and generally be more active. They can introduce a rewards based system for users who have high activity that can be redeemed as discounts on products.\n\nNext I wanted to see trends in how users wear their devices. I used the following steps:\n\nFirst, lets see how many days are in our dataset from our merged table titled daily_data","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"n_unique(daily_data$date)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This shows that our dataset covers a time period of 31 days.\n\n-2. I grouped users by the 3 categories shown below to find out how they wear their devices:\n\n**-perfect use: device worn between 21-31 days-, -moderate use: device worn between 11-20 days-, -low use: device worn between 6 and 10 days-, -extremely low: users who use their device between 1-5 days-**\n\nI created a new data frame using the classification above and grouping by id","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_use <- daily_data %>%\n  group_by(id) %>%\n  summarize(days_used=sum(n())) %>%\n  mutate(frequency = case_when(\n    days_used >= 1 & days_used <= 5 ~ \"extremely low use\",\n    days_used >= 6 & days_used <= 10 ~ \"low use\",\n    days_used >= 11 & days_used <= 20 ~ \"moderate use\", \n    days_used >= 21 & days_used <= 31 ~ \"high use\", \n  ))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i converted the categories to percentage for easy visualization in a pie chart","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"percentage_daily_use <- daily_use %>%\n  group_by(frequency) %>%\n  summarise(total = n()) %>%\n  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%\n  group_by(frequency) %>%\n  summarise(total_percent = total / totals) %>%\n  mutate(labels = scales::percent(total_percent))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I previewed the dataframe","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"head(percentage_daily_use)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"then formatted frequency from chr to fct","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"percentage_daily_use$frequency <- factor(percentage_daily_use$frequency, levels = c(\"extremely low use\", \"high use\", \"low use\", \"moderate use\"))","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then previewed the dataframe again to confirm its now in fct","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"head(percentage_daily_use)","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then i plotted a pie charge to visualize how the users are categorized","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"percentage_daily_use %>%\n  ggplot(aes(x=\"\",y=total_percent, fill=labels)) +\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 1)+\n  coord_polar(\"y\", start=0)+\n  theme_minimal()+\n  theme(axis.title.x= element_blank(),\n        axis.title.y = element_blank(),\n        panel.border = element_blank(), \n        panel.grid = element_blank(), \n        axis.ticks = element_blank(),\n        axis.text.x = element_blank(),\n        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=14, face = \"bold\")) +\n  geom_text(aes(label = labels),\n            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#00e673\",\"#cd2626\",\"#ffbbff\",\"#006633\"),\n                    labels = c(\"Moderate use - 11 to 20 days\",\"Extremely low use - 1 to 5 days\", \"Low use - 6 to 10 days\",\"High use - 21 to 31 days\"))+\n  labs(title=\"Daily use of smart device\")","metadata":{},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"![image.png](attachment:c3b8e5dc-fcd3-43b1-8762-4de5d4fb2d49.png)","metadata":{},"attachments":{"c3b8e5dc-fcd3-43b1-8762-4de5d4fb2d49.png":{"image/png":""}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This shows that 33% of the users only wore their device between 1-5 days. This is extremely low. Bellabeat can use this information to send reminders to users via its app at a certain time of the day. This will help remind their customers to wear their devices.\n\n**Phase 6 : ACT**\n\nThis is a summary of the recommendations made from the insights gotten from this analysis.\n\n1. Bellabeat can first collect an analyze its own data using a larger sample number and over a longer period of time. This will ensure the data used has integrity, is reliable, is relevant and has lesser chanaces of being biased\n2. Bellabeat can include features in its app that sends notifications to its customers to be more active, get enough sleep, talk more steps daily especially on weekends and wear their devices consistently.\n3. Bellabeat can introduce a rewards system that will encourage its customers to wear their smart devices everyday so they can have accurate data about their general health and wellbeing.\n\n\n**ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS**\n\nI would like to acknowledge the following projects that helped me with this project and gave me ideas for my plots.\n\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/malavikav4/bellabeat-case-study-using-r\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/macarenalacasa/capstone-case-study-bellabeat/notebook","metadata":{}}]}